It's pretty ironic, really. Just having death as a semi-imaginary Plan B for everything.. seems to lift a weight off of my shoulders. One minute I'm sitting in my chair, all dramatic and paralyzed, thinking about my problems.. next minute, I'm laughing my ass off. lol
&nbsp;
I just deleted my Facebook, and that also lifted a weight off of my shoulders. People just don't have interesting shit to talk about on there.. or maybe I just don't have any friends in real life, cause I'm a nerd and I like to talk about anarchy, politics, computer software, etc. instead of posting a trillion selfies.
&nbsp;
I hate how this world revolves around money. I hate feeling like a sucker for the dollar.
&nbsp;
To be honest, though.. these days I'm not worried about money at all. I'm more worried about leaving behind something good for humanity, even if I can't make a living out of it. Anything. And also speaking out and saying things that people are too scared to say. 
&nbsp;
Ideas are bulletproof.

I considered implementing it for KopyKate.. for a minute. lol
&nbsp;
But then, now that I think about it. It's one of those things that tends to hurt small creators the most, because a lot of the times, what trolls can do .. is link a random video to a forum for fun, e.g. a video that talks about transgender people, or whatever.. and then start mass-disliking.
&nbsp;
The dislike bar is almost embedded in our minds as implying 'something is wrong here' or 'There's gonna be lots of trash in the comments.' or alternatively... 'this could be a scam or a misleading title'.. in the case of more honest applications of the disliking system. (but then, that's what Report is for, isn't it..)
&nbsp;
Of course, creators can always disable ratings for their videos, but it's a catch-22; having your ratings disabled often makes you come across as 'I don't value people's opinions, I'm an authoritarian and possibly a douchebag.' 
&nbsp;
So maybe the only way to put an end to the drama is to do away with this system. If people like a video, they'll seed it, too. If not, well.. then it'll just float around with 1 like, and people can make better videos if they want, without the drama.

Yesterday my mother told me how they were talking on the news about the obscene amounts of money that video game developers are currently making.. and how it's a very recession-proof line of work where you're never gonna be out of a job.
&nbsp;
I used to do modding on an open source video game when I was 8.. back in the days of SourceForge. In fact, it's currently on GitHub.. lol
&nbsp;
https://github.com/egoboo/egoboo
&nbsp;
Of course, I kinda grew up with the mindset that there's probably not much money to be made in video game development these days, considering how easy it is to crack yourself a free copy. Mind you, I'm not complaining about piracy here, lol .. .. more about, the lack of alternative business models for artists and developers on the interwebs, beyond simply forcing users to buy a physical copy, or forcing them to put up with annoying ads selling products they don't give a shit about.. or having to resort to crowdfunding a.k.a Cyber-begging / panhandling.
&nbsp;
Obviously, there's video game companies making obscene amounts of money as we speak, but I have the feeling that it's one of those industries where you're either a big player, a big winner .. or a sore loser.. kinda like the music / film industry. There's no entry-level jobs, no middle-ground. This is just my opinion btw - I hope somebody can prove me wrong.
&nbsp;
I'm currently working on an ActionScript 3.0 framework for one of my animated series, and will soon release the code on GitHub, too. Basically, the way it works is that it allows you to automate animations. You have a certain set of body movements, facial expressions, etc. and then you control them all using code algorithms, combinations, patterns, etc. 
&nbsp;
This saves you a lot of time because frankly, animation is a very time-consuming hobby involving mundane and repetitive tasks, and even if you put a lot of effort into it .. if it doesn't have a good story line, it's gonna suck .. and if you're a creator yourself, you will sooner or later know how utterly exhausting, demotivating and depressing it is to put hours and days and months of effort into a project, only to have it pissed on by the wrath of the internets.. so you may as well just let AI take care of the animating part and the repetitive tasks, so that way you can put more effort and focus into the story. lol
&nbsp;
The characters are also structured in a way that allows you to easily modify them, using a library that contains bitmaps and various images.. many of them downloaded off of the internet. haha
&nbsp;
Anyhow.. I actually plan on getting back into video game development after that. One thing I really hate about video games these days is that you have to sit on the computer for prolonged periods of time staring at a screen. I tend to be really restless and have to get up and be on the move every 30-40 minutes or so, which is why I've largely quit video games, and why I'd rather watch YouTube videos than watch a 2-hour-long movie. 
&nbsp;
Wouldn't it be nice to have a Virtual Reality MMORPG? Actually, that's a pretty dangerous idea.. a path to the matrix. It would get people up and going, but they'll probably never leave the house after that.
&nbsp;
Another problem in video games is the Escapism. We live in an age of rising mental health issues, loneliness, obesity, eating disorders, etc. I think it's about time that video games got a good rap and helped us solve these issues. I want a video game that can help you find love, get laid, get fit. A game that, in many ways, can bring us back to the old days where people got together and joined clubs and went to church every sunday and went on adventures together, etc. . . without the church part, of course! ;-)
&nbsp;
I think this would also require us to make video game characters more realistic. On the internet, anybody can be a slender anime-girl with big, fat boobs.. even a man. Anybody can photoshop themselves on Facebook and only show the best part of their lives. It's time that we also embraced tragedy and imperfection.. and a good dose of reality here and then.....
&nbsp;
But then, wouldn't that defeat the purpose of video games; Escaping reality?

